  "patterns": [
    {
      "name": "Light Path and Shadows",
      "what": "Sometimes draws or chooses light arrows starting from the eye instead of the light source, and occasionally forgets that objects closer to a light source cast bigger shadows.",
      "specific_examples": [
        {
          "questionRef": "[79]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "Kaiyangnggg chose arrows showing light traveling from the eye to the door, rather than from the lamp to the door and then reflecting into the eye."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[68]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He mixed up the order of shapes casting a shadow, forgetting that the shape closest to the torch will cast the largest shadow."
        }
      ],
      "strategic_advice": "When you see questions about seeing objects or shadows, remember these two rules:\n- **Light always starts from a source** (like a lamp or the sun). To see an object, light must bounce off it and travel **into your eyes**.\n- For shadow questions, remember: **Closer to the light = Bigger shadow**. Draw a quick line from the torch past the object to see how big the shadow will be!",
      "trigger_keywords": [
        "direction of light rays",
        "shadow",
        "screen",
        "torch"
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Conductor and Insulator Mix-Up",
      "what": "Occasionally confuses which materials are good conductors of heat (like metal) and which are poor conductors (like air, wood, or glass).",
      "specific_examples": [
        {
          "questionRef": "[38]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "Kaiyangnggg thought a glass container would cool down the fastest, instead of a metal container which is a much better conductor of heat."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[28]",
          "type": "oeq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He missed mentioning that the trapped air in the corrugated cup sleeve is a poor conductor of heat, which is the key reason it slows down heat transfer to the fingers."
        }
      ],
      "strategic_advice": "When a question compares materials like metal, plastic, wood, or glass, it is testing **heat conductivity**.\n- **Metals are good conductors**: they gain and lose heat very quickly.\n- **Air, wood, plastic, and glass are poor conductors**: they trap heat and slow down heat transfer. Always use the exact phrase **'poor conductor of heat'** in your written explanations!",
      "trigger_keywords": [
        "different materials",
        "lowest temperature",
        "keep cold",
        "prevent scalding"
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Heat and State Mix-Up",
      "what": "Tends to think heat is only gained during a change of state (like melting), and sometimes mixes up whether a process like condensation involves gaining or losing heat.",
      "specific_examples": [
        {
          "questionRef": "[35]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "Kaiyangnggg looked at a heating graph and thought the ice/water only gained heat during the melting phase, missing that it also gains heat when the temperature rises."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[4]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He thought that water changing from a gas to a liquid at 100°C is boiling, rather than condensation which involves losing heat."
        }
      ],
      "strategic_advice": "When analyzing heat graphs or state changes, keep these facts in mind:\n- If a substance is over a heat source, it is **always gaining heat**, even if the temperature line on the graph is flat (changing state) or going up (getting hotter).\n- Remember your state changes: **Melting and Boiling = Gaining Heat**. **Condensation and Freezing = Losing Heat**.",
      "trigger_keywords": [
        "gaining heat",
        "loses heat",
        "changes from gas to liquid",
        "graph"
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "One Step Short",
      "what": "Often understands the science concept perfectly, but stops one step short of writing the exact keywords or full comparisons the markers are looking for.",
      "specific_examples": [
        {
          "questionRef": "[29]",
          "type": "oeq",
          "whatWentWrong": "Kaiyangnggg correctly stated that cooking two packets of fish balls takes longer, but forgot to mention the key reason: there is **more mass** to be heated up."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[66]",
          "type": "oeq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He explained that the chocolate filling burst out because it expanded, but missed stating that it **gained heat** and expanded **more than** the bun."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[30]",
          "type": "oeq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He defined boiling as reaching a certain temperature, but missed the crucial science definition: a **change in state from liquid to gas**."
        }
      ],
      "strategic_advice": "When you see **'explain why'**, always check if you have included the **science keywords** (like 'gained heat', 'more mass', 'change in state'). If a question involves two things (like chocolate filling and a bun), make sure to use **comparison words** (like 'expanded **more than**'). Don't just talk about one!",
      "trigger_keywords": [
        "explain why",
        "give a reason",
        "state what"
      ]
    }
  ],
